Use `jazz-files`. Keep the conventional tables and columns exactly as the helpers expect:

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  file_parts: s.table({
    data: s.bytes(),
  }),
  files: s.table({
    name: s.string().optional(),
    mimeType: s.string(),
    partIds: s.array(s.ref("file_parts")),
    partSizes: s.array(s.int()),
  }),
  uploads: s.table({
    owner_id: s.string(),
    label: s.string(),
    fileId: s.ref("files"),
  }),
};
```

Permission shape for private uploads owned by `uploads`:

```ts
export default s.definePermissions(app, ({ policy, allowedTo, session }) => {
  policy.uploads.allowRead.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });
  policy.uploads.allowInsert.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });
  policy.uploads.allowUpdate.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });
  policy.uploads.allowDelete.where({ owner_id: session.user_id });

  policy.files.allowInsert.where({});
  policy.file_parts.allowInsert.where({});

  policy.files.allowRead.where(allowedTo.readReferencing(policy.uploads, "fileId"));
  policy.file_parts.allowRead.where(allowedTo.readReferencing(policy.files, "partIds"));
  policy.files.allowDelete.where(allowedTo.deleteReferencing(policy.uploads, "fileId"));
  policy.file_parts.allowDelete.where(allowedTo.deleteReferencing(policy.files, "partIds"));
});
```

Store the returned file row ID on `uploads.fileId`. Treat `files` and `file_parts` as write-once; replacement should create a new file, update the parent, then clean up the old one.

Use `jazz-files`. For upload success that means every chunk reached edge, create the file with an explicit edge write tier and wait for the parent row at the same tier:

```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });

const upload = await db
  .insert(app.uploads, {
    owner_id: session.user_id,
    label: "Profile photo",
    fileId: file.id,
  })
  .wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

For download when local chunks may be incomplete, read with a tier that can fetch a complete remote snapshot and distinguish missing file from incomplete data:

```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  return { kind: "ready", blob };
} catch (error) {
  if (error.name === "FileNotFoundError") {
    return { kind: "missing" };
  }
  if (error.name === "IncompleteFileDataError") {
    return { kind: "incomplete", reason: error.reason };
  }
  throw error;
}
```

Use `loadFileAsStream(...)` instead if the consumer can process sequentially. A stronger read tier can wait for remote completeness, but it will not fix corrupt metadata or a genuinely missing part.

Use `jazz-files`. Delete in dependency order so inherited delete permissions still exist while you clean up children:

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  }
  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}

db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```

Order matters:
1. Load the parent upload.
2. Load the referenced file while the parent relationship still authorises access.
3. Delete every `file_parts` row.
4. Delete the `files` row.
5. Delete the `uploads` row last.

Do not delete the parent first, or inherited delete permissions for the file and parts may disappear before cleanup finishes.

Create one application-owned projection per query and pair it with a strict decoder. In Rust, `JazzClient::query(...)` returns `Vec<(ObjectId, Vec<Value>)>`, so treat that as the raw boundary and immediately convert it into a typed struct.

Define the query projection and decoder together so column order cannot drift:

```rust
struct TodoRow {
    id: ObjectId,
    title: String,
    done: bool,
    description: Option<String>,
}

fn decode_todo(id: ObjectId, values: &[Value]) -> Result<TodoRow, AppError> {
    if values.len() != 3 {
        return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch("todos projection length"));
    }

    let title = match &values[0] {
        Value::Text(v) => v.clone(),
        _ => return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch("title must be text")),
    };
    let done = match &values[1] {
        Value::Boolean(v) => *v,
        _ => return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch("done must be boolean")),
    };
    let description = match &values[2] {
        Value::Null => None,
        Value::Text(v) => Some(v.clone()),
        _ => return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch("description must be text|null")),
    };

    Ok(TodoRow { id, title, done, description })
}
```

Use `SchemaBuilder`, `TableSchema::builder`, and `row_input!` for writes; do not build ad hoc JSON fixtures. For repeated access, expose small repository-style functions such as `list_todos(&JazzClient) -> Result<Vec<TodoRow>, AppError>` and `mark_done(&JazzClient, id) -> Result<BatchId, AppError>`. After writes, wait on the returned batch at the durability tier your contract requires, rather than returning success from local optimistic state.

Use one long-lived process `JazzClient` with the service's backend transport credential, then scope it per request with `client.for_session(session)` after authenticating the caller. The scoped client must perform both the read and the write, so row visibility and authorship are evaluated as the caller rather than as trusted backend code.

Endpoint shape:
1. Verify the bearer token and derive a stable Jazz `Session`.
2. Create `let db = app_state.client.for_session(session);`.
3. Query the target row through `db`; treat filtered rows as `404`.
4. Perform `update(...)` through `db`.
5. Await `wait_for_batch(batch_id, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer)` or `GlobalServer` inside `tokio::time::timeout(...)`.
6. Requery through `db` and return that representation.

Skeleton:

```rust
async fn update_todo(
    State(state): State<AppState>,
    Authenticated(session): Authenticated,
    Path(id): Path<ObjectId>,
    Json(body): Json<UpdateTodoBody>,
) -> Result<Json<TodoRow>, ApiError> {
    let db = state.client.for_session(session);

    let existing = load_todo(&db, id).await?.ok_or(ApiError::NotFound)?;

    let batch_id = db.update(
        existing.id,
        vec![("done".into(), Value::Boolean(body.done))],
    )?;

    tokio::time::timeout(
        std::time::Duration::from_secs(5),
        db.wait_for_batch(batch_id, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer),
    )
    .await
    .map_err(|_| ApiError::Timeout)??;

    let updated = load_todo(&db, id).await?.ok_or(ApiError::NotFound)?;
    Ok(Json(updated))
}
```

Map failures deliberately: `401` for bad auth, `404` for missing or policy-filtered rows, `403` for authoritative rejection, `504` for durability timeout, and an internal error for decode/schema mismatches. Do not return raw `JazzError` strings to the client.
